ty="1" transform="matrix(1,0,0,1,0,0)"><path stroke="url(#__lottie_element_1012)" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="miter" fill-opacity="0" stroke-miterlimit="4" stroke-opacity="1" stroke-width="2" d=" M0.33899998664855957,-14.996000289916992 C5.2829999923706055,-14.88599967956543 9.640000343322754,-12.378999710083008 12.293000221252441,-8.593000411987305"></path></g></g><g style="display: none;" wfd-invisible="true"><g><path stroke="url(#__lottie_element_1008)" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="miter" fill-opacity="0" stroke-miterlimit="4"></path></g></g><g style="display: none;" wfd-invisible="true"><g><path stroke="url(#__lottie_element_1004)" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="miter" fill-opacity="0" stroke-miterlimit="4"></path></g></g><g style="display: none;" wfd-invisible="true"><g><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="miter" fill-opacity="0" stroke-miterlimit="4"></path></g></g><g style="display: none;" wfd-invisible="true"><g><path stroke="url(#__lottie_element_997)" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="miter" fill-opacity="0" stroke-miterlimit="4"></path></g></g></g></svg></div></div></bard-avatar><!----><!----></div><!----><div _ngcontent-ng-c1883881203="" class="response-container-content ng-tns-c1883881203-46"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><div _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" class="response-content ng-tns-c1883881203-46"><!----><div _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" class="thoughts-container ng-star-inserted"><!----></div><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><h2 _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" class="cdk-visually-hidden ng-star-inserted">Gemini a dit</h2><!----><!----><structured-content-container _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" class="model-response-text processing-state-visible ng-star-inserted" _nghost-ng-c4085131935="" style="height: auto;"><div _ngcontent-ng-c4085131935="" class="container"><message-content _ngcontent-ng-c4085131935="" _nghost-ng-c3807329646="" id="message-content-id-r_40c2b07a208f6460" class="ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c3807329646="" inline-copy-host="" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;" id="model-response-message-contentr_40c2b07a208f6460" aria-live="off" aria-busy="false" dir="ltr"><p data-path-to-node="0"><b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="0">Error Level Analysis (ELA)</b> is a forensic technique used to identify manipulated areas in a digital image by analyzing the compression levels within the file.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">When an image is saved in a lossy format (like <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="47">JPEG</b>), the entire image is compressed at a specific "error level." If you modify a specific part of that image—by pasting in a new cell, a gel band, or a person—and then resave it, that modified section will have a different error level than the rest of the original photo.</p><hr data-path-to-node="2"><h3 data-path-to-node="3">🔍 How It Works</h3><p data-path-to-node="4">Think of an image like a piece of bread. When it's fresh (original), the texture is even. If you "toast" it (save it as a JPEG), it gets crunchy all over. If you then paste a piece of fresh, untoasted bread onto the toast and put it back in the toaster for a second, the new piece will look and feel different from the part that was toasted twice.</p><ul data-path-to-node="5"><li><p data-path-to-node="5,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Original Areas:</b> Appear as dark, uniform "noise" or grain.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="5,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Modified Areas:</b> Appear as bright, high-contrast white or colored clusters. These "glow" because the pixels were resaved at a different frequency than the original background.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="6">🧪 What ELA Detects in Scientific Papers</h3><p data-path-to-node="7">In the context of tools like <b data-path-to-node="7" data-index-in-node="29">Proofig</b> or your Chrome extension, ELA is used to spot:</p><ol start="1" data-path-to-node="8"><li><p data-path-to-node="8,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="8,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Pasted Gel Bands:</b> If a band was moved from one lane to another, the edges of the "pasted" box will often glow brightly under ELA.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="8,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="8,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Background Cleaning:</b> If an author used a "healing brush" or "clone stamp" to hide noise or debris in a microscope image, those areas will show a different error level than the natural texture of the slide.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="8,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="8,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">Splicing:</b> If two different photos were merged into one figure, the boundary where they meet will usually have a massive spike in ELA values.</p></li></ol><hr data-path-to-node="9"><h3 data-path-to-node="10">⚠️ The Limitations (False Positives)</h3><p data-path-to-node="11">ELA is a powerful "smoke detector," but it isn't always "fire." You have to be careful of:</p><ul data-path-to-node="12"><li><p data-path-to-node="12,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="12,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">High-Contrast Edges:</b> Natural sharp edges (like black text on a white background) will always "glow" in ELA. This is normal and doesn't mean the image is fake.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="12,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="12,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Multiple Saves:</b> If an image has been screenshotted and resaved 10 times, the ELA becomes "muddy" and harder to read.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="12,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="12,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">Scaling:</b> If an author widened or shrunk a photo, the ELA levels can become distorted across the whole image.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node="13"><h3 data-path-to-node="14">🛠️ How to use it in your Extension</h3><p data-path-to-node="15">When your Chrome extension grabs an image, it sends the URL to a tool like <b data-path-to-node="15" data-index-in-node="75">Forensically</b>. You should look for <b data-path-to-node="15" data-index-in-node="109">uniformity</b>.</p><ul data-path-to-node="16"><li><p data-path-to-node="16,0,0">If the entire image looks like a "starry night" of even, dim pixels, it’s likely untouched.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="16,1,0">If one specific band in a Western Blot is glowing like a neon sign while the others are dim, you have found a potential manipulation.</p></li></ul><p data-path-to-node="17"><b data-path-to-node="17" data-index-in-node="0">Would you like me to show you how to read an ELA map so you can tell the difference between a "natural edge" and a "pasted band"?</b></p></div></message-content><!----></div></structured-content-container><!----><!----><div _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" class="response-footer gap complete"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><div _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" role="status" class="stopped-draft-message gds-body-l gds-italic ng-star-inserted" hidden="" wfd-invisible="true">Vous avez interrompu cette réponse</div><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----></div></div><!----><sensitive-memories-banner _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" _nghost-ng-c3363139195="" class="ng-star-inserted" style=""><!----></sensitive-memories-banner><!----><!----><!----></div></div><div _ngcontent-ng-c1883881203="" class="response-container-footer ng-tns-c1883881203-46 ng-star-inserted"><!----><!----><message-actions _ngcontent-ng-c3748022998="" footer="" _nghost-ng-c3060034751="" class="ng-tns-c3060034751-48 ng-star-inserted hide-action-bar" style=""><div _ngcontent-ng-c3060034751="" class="actions-container-v2 ng-tns-c3060034751-48"><div _ngcontent-ng-c3060034751="" class="buttons-container-v2 ng-tns-c3060034751-48 ng-star-inserted"><!----><thumb-up-button _ngcontent-ng-c3060034751="" _nghost-ng-c885881154="" class="ng-tns-c3060034751-48 ng-